[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.9: Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Regulated · **Estimated Cost:** ~$3-12 per active member per month (depends on engagement frequency, channel mix, model choice, RAG depth, referral-tracking integration depth, cross-system reconciliation overhead, and human-care-manager backstop staffing)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m David is 67. Two months ago he had a heart attack. He was in the hospital for four days, in the cardiac cath lab once, in a step-down unit for two of those days, and home by the end of the week with a stack of discharge paperwork, eight new prescriptions, three follow-up appointments scheduled at three different locations, a referral to cardiac rehab, a referral to a cardiologist his hospitalist recommended (who is not the cardiologist David's primary care doctor usually refers to), instructions to follow up with his primary care doctor within two weeks, instructions to schedule a sleep study because the inpatient team noticed he had probable sleep apnea, instructions to follow up with his endocrinologist about his diabetes (which was now harder to manage on the new beta blocker), and a printed business card for a nurse named Janet from the hospital's discharge team who told him to call her if anything came up. The discharge paperwork is sitting on his kitchen counter. So is the printed business card. So are the eight pill bottles. So is the home blood-pressure cuff the hospital nurse showed him how to use. David's wife Lin, who is 64 and works full-time as a dental hygienist, is doing her best to keep track of everything, but she also has a job and a household and a mother in assisted living who she visits on weekends.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What happens next is the predictable failure pattern of post-acute-event care coordination in the United States. David tries to schedule the cardiology follow-up. The cardiologist's office tells him they can see him in five weeks. David is not sure if five weeks is okay. The discharge paperwork said "follow up with cardiology within two weeks," but the cardiologist's office is a different practice from the one David's PCP usually refers to, and David is not sure who to ask. He calls Janet. Janet does not pick up. He leaves a voicemail. He waits two days and calls back. Janet calls him back the third day, listens, says she will look into it, and calls back another two days later to say she has gotten him an appointment with a different cardiologist (the one his PCP usually works with) for next Tuesday. David shows up next Tuesday. The cardiologist's office has not received the discharge summary. David has to explain his hospitalization from memory, including the specific medications and the specific procedure, while the cardiologist tries to pull records from the hospital system, which uses a different EHR. The visit ends with a note in the cardiologist's chart, a small medication adjustment, and an instruction to follow up with the cardiologist again in three months and with the cardiac rehab program "as soon as you can get in." David leaves with the third version of his medication list and is not entirely sure which one is correct.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m He tries to schedule cardiac rehab. The cardiac rehab program is at the hospital, in a different building from the cardiologist's office. The intake coordinator tells him there is a four-week waiting list for new starts. David asks if there is anywhere else. The intake coordinator says she can check, but most of the area programs have similar waits. David goes on the waiting list. He does not start cardiac rehab for six weeks after his discharge, which is well past the window in which cardiac rehab provides the largest benefit for outcomes after a heart attack. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for early cardiac rehabilitation initiation is well-established with stronger benefit when started in the early post-discharge window; specific window definitions vary in the literature -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m He follows up with his primary care doctor a week and a half after discharge. The PCP has gotten the discharge summary, in the form of a 27-page PDF that arrived through the regional health information exchange three days after discharge. The PCP has not had time to read it carefully. The PCP and David spend the visit catching up, with David explaining what happened in the hospital and the PCP trying to make sense of the medication list, the new diagnoses, and the specialist follow-up plan. The PCP makes a note to follow up with the cardiologist's office about a small discrepancy in the recommended antiplatelet therapy. The PCP also notices that the discharge plan included a sleep study referral that David has not yet acted on; the PCP does not bring this up because David is overwhelmed and the sleep study can wait. The PCP also notices that David's endocrinology follow-up has slipped; the PCP does not bring this up either, for the same reason. David leaves the PCP visit feeling supported but also feeling like he is forgetting something.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The sleep study does not get scheduled until four months later, when David's wife notices an envelope on the counter and asks about it. By then the sleep study order has expired and a new order is required. David's wife emails the PCP through the patient portal. The PCP's MA writes a new order. David schedules the sleep study, but the next available appointment is six weeks out. David is eventually diagnosed with moderate obstructive sleep apnea, gets a CPAP, and benefits from it; the diagnosis was about six months later than it should have been.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The endocrinology follow-up never happens. David's PCP starts managing the diabetes adjustments instead, because the beta blocker has changed the glycemic dynamics and David is finding the endocrinologist hard to schedule with. The endocrinologist's chart eventually gets a "lost to follow-up" note. The PCP does her best, but she is not an endocrinologist, and David's A1c drifts up over the following year before stabilizing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The cardiac rehab eventually starts at week six. David goes for the first three sessions and then stops; the program meets in the middle of the day, three days a week, for twelve weeks, and David's part-time consulting work makes the schedule hard. He is not the only patient who quietly drops out of cardiac rehab; <!-- TODO: verify; cardiac rehab completion rates in the U.S. are documented in the published literature with substantial drop-off documented and substantial racial, ethnic, and socioeconomic disparities; specific figures vary --> the program completion rate at his hospital is well below national targets, which is well below the rate that the evidence supports for outcomes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A year later, David is doing roughly okay. His cardiac function has stabilized. His blood pressure is mostly controlled. His A1c is higher than it should be. He is not on the optimal antiplatelet regimen but neither is he on a clearly wrong one. He has not done cardiac rehab. He has been diagnosed with sleep apnea and is using CPAP. He has had two cardiology visits, four PCP visits, no endocrinology visits, three rounds of labs, two emergency room visits for unrelated concerns, and approximately seventeen hours of his own time spent on phone calls trying to schedule, reschedule, reconcile, and follow up. His wife Lin estimates she has spent another fifteen hours of her own time on the same. The healthcare system, looking at David's claims, sees a fully-engaged patient. Janet, the nurse from the hospital's discharge team, has not heard from David in eleven months and assumes he is fine.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is the central problem of care coordination in the United States in 2026. The clinical knowledge for managing David's care is not the bottleneck. The medications work. The follow-up plans work. The cardiac rehab works. The endocrinology follow-up works. The sleep apnea diagnosis works. What does not work, reliably, is the system of getting all of those things to happen, in the right order, with the right hand-offs, with the right information following the patient across each transition, and with someone watching for the things that fall through the cracks. The system is built around individual encounters, each of which is documented well; what is documented poorly is the space between encounters, where most of care coordination actually happens.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The economic and clinical impact of this gap is enormous. Care transitions, particularly post-acute-event transitions, are the single highest-leverage moment in healthcare. <!-- TODO: verify; the impact of care transitions on readmission rates, downstream events, and total cost of care is documented in studies including the Care Transitions Intervention work by Coleman et al., the Better Outcomes for Older Adults through Safe Transitions (BOOST) program, and ongoing CMS readmission-reduction work --> Patients who get good care coordination after a heart attack have lower rates of readmission, lower mortality, better functional recovery, and lower total cost of care. Patients who do not, get worse outcomes by every measure. The labor model for delivering good care coordination is the same labor model as for chronic disease management: nurse care coordinators, transitional-care nurses, social workers, and care managers, who are expensive, finite, and reserved for the highest-risk members.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m David, with one heart attack, three follow-up needs, and one missed referral, is in the broad middle of the post-discharge population. He is not high-risk enough to qualify for intensive care management at most institutions. He is also not low-risk enough that nothing will go wrong if he is left to coordinate his own care. He is one of millions of patients who fall in the space where the system has neither the manual capacity to coordinate his care for him nor the discipline to make it easy for him to coordinate his own.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Previous generations of care-coordination tools tried to address this with patient portals and discharge-instruction apps. The patient logged in. The patient saw a list of upcoming appointments and a list of things to do. Some apps added reminders. Some apps added secure messaging with the care team. The clinical evidence for these tools was, broadly, that they helped patients who were already organized and motivated; they did not meaningfully help the patients in the broad middle who were the ones most likely to lose track of things. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for patient portal use and care coordination is mixed; specific findings vary by tool, population, and outcome measure --> The fundamental problem these products had was that they made the patient do the work. The patient still had to remember to log in, still had to remember which appointment was next, still had to remember which referral was outstanding, still had to remember to chase down the medical records the next clinician needed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What changed, around 2023 and continuing since, is that conversational AI got good enough to make care coordination feel like a relationship with a coordinator rather than a list of tasks. A patient who would not log into the patient portal will, sometimes, respond to a text message that says "Hey David, your cardiology appointment is on Tuesday at 10:30. We've sent your records over to Dr. Patel's office; they should have everything they need. The address is 240 Main Street, Building C, second floor. Anything you want to bring up with Dr. Patel beyond what we discussed last week?" That message comes from a system that has read his discharge plan, has tracked his referrals, has confirmed the records went out, and has remembered the things he wanted to talk about. The system is not a person. The patient mostly knows that. The patient also, in the right product design, talks to it anyway, because the alternative was nothing, and because the message is genuinely useful.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This recipe is about that system. The care coordination assistant is the conversational AI use case where the architectural patterns from the previous chapter 11 recipes converge into a multi-system orchestration product, and where several entirely new patterns enter the picture: multi-provider context awareness across systems that do not natively share data, longitudinal referral and care-transition tracking with explicit completion semantics, cross-encounter information continuity, social-determinants overlay, family-and-caregiver integration, and a coordination-rather-than-coaching engagement style that is meaningfully different from the chronic-disease coach.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the assistant that helps patients navigate complex care journeys, particularly journeys that span multiple providers, multiple systems, and multiple care episodes. The journeys include post-acute-care transitions (post-discharge, post-procedure, post-ED), specialist-coordination journeys (oncology with multiple specialists across surgery, medical oncology, radiation oncology, supportive-care, social-work, nutrition, rehab, and primary-care), maternity journeys (prenatal-through-postpartum spanning OB, primary care, pediatrics, social services), behavioral-health-and-medical co-management, complex-pediatrics (a child with multiple specialists, school-based services, and family-support needs), and end-of-life-care coordination across hospice, home-health, palliative-care, and family.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a chronic-disease coach. Recipe 11.7 covers chronic-disease coaching with a focus on day-to-day self-management for established conditions. The care coordination assistant focuses on the orchestration of care across providers, settings, and episodes, with the patient as the focal point and the coordinator's perspective as the operating mode. The two architectures share infrastructure (longitudinal store, conversation handler, citation discipline, audit pipeline) but diverge in their core task surface.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a triage bot. Recipe 11.6 covers acute-symptom triage. The care coordination assistant handles ongoing coordination of established care plans; when a patient surfaces an acute concern, the assistant hands off to triage workflows or to direct emergency routing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a primary-care substitute. The assistant does not provide diagnosis, does not adjust medications, does not interpret lab results beyond surfacing them with appropriate framing, and does not provide clinical advice beyond what is grounded in the patient's care plan and the institution's clinical guidance. The assistant supports coordination; the clinical decisions live with clinicians.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a substitute for the human care coordinator workforce. The assistant extends the workforce; it does not replace it. The workforce remains responsible for the cases that need clinical judgment, for the coordination work that requires phone-and-relationship navigation across institutions, and for the patients whose situations fall outside the assistant's scope. The economics work because the assistant handles the routine touches while the human coordinators focus where their judgment matters.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a one-size-fits-all product. A post-discharge coordinator for a cardiac patient is meaningfully different from a post-discharge coordinator for an oncology patient or a maternity coordinator or a complex-pediatrics coordinator. Each journey type has its own care-plan vocabulary, its own milestone semantics, its own escalation logic, its own provider-network considerations, and its own family-and-caregiver patterns. Most institutions deploy a multi-journey coordination architecture with journey-specific protocols layered on a shared conversational core.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a regulatory afterthought. Patient-facing care-coordination software, particularly when it surfaces clinical information, makes scheduling decisions, and interprets discharge plans for the patient, has specific compliance considerations including HIPAA, the Information Blocking Rule under the 21st Century Cures Act, state-specific patient-portal-and-record-access laws, and (for some functionality) the FDA SaMD line. <!-- TODO: verify; the regulatory positioning of patient-facing care-coordination software depends on the specific functionality; the Information Blocking Rule under the 21st Century Cures Act sets specific requirements for patient access to electronic health information; the FDA SaMD framework applies depending on specific functionality --> The institutional regulatory team is involved from architectural design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The deployment timeline is multi-quarter. The journey-content investment is multi-quarter. The cross-system integration work (EHR, scheduling, referral management, HIE, pharmacy, durable medical equipment, home health, social services) is multi-quarter and is usually the longest pole in the project. The institutional-capability development for the human coordinator workforce is multi-quarter. The outcome demonstration is multi-year.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the assistant's value is not in any individual conversation. The value is in the cumulative reduction of things falling through the cracks: the appointment that gets scheduled in the right window because the assistant nudged the patient at the right moment, the referral that gets completed because the assistant tracked it through to closure, the record that gets to the next clinician because the assistant pushed it through the institution's records-release workflow, the early-warning escalation to the human coordinator because the assistant noticed the patient had not picked up a critical post-discharge medication. None of these is dramatic in isolation. The accumulation is what changes outcomes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Conversational Care Coordination Grounded In Multi-Provider Context, Care-Plan Tracking, and Workflow Orchestration
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Care Coordination Has Resisted Digital Tools For As Long As It Has
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, as a clinical workflow, has been a phone-and-fax-and-paper-clip problem for almost all of its history. The reason is structural. Care coordination requires holding, simultaneously, a model of the patient's full clinical journey across providers and settings, a model of each individual provider's workflow and information needs, a model of the institutional and inter-institutional information-flow rules (which records can move where, with what authorization, in what format), a model of the scheduling constraints (each provider's availability, each procedure's preparation requirements, each patient's logistical constraints), and a model of the patient's social and personal context (transportation, language, work schedule, family caregivers, financial constraints, health literacy, cultural framing). The model lives mostly in the heads of the people doing the coordination work: the discharge nurse, the case manager, the patient navigator, the oncology nurse coordinator, the high-risk-pregnancy social worker. When the coordination is done well, it is because someone has held all of this in their head for the patient, has made the calls, has tracked the loose ends, and has chased the delays. When the coordination is done poorly, it is because no single person has held all of this for the patient, and the patient (or their family) has been left to coordinate their own care, with predictable results.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The digital tools, until recently, have been data infrastructure rather than coordination tools. EHRs solved the chart-as-shared-record problem within an institution. HIEs solved (partially) the chart-sharing-across-institutions problem. Patient portals solved (partially) the patient-as-record-viewer problem. Scheduling systems solved the appointment-booking problem within institutions. Referral-management systems solved the referral-as-data-record problem. None of these solved the coordination problem itself, which is the problem of orchestrating activity across all of these systems toward the patient's care goals while keeping the patient and the family informed and engaged.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The labor model for coordination, where it exists, is the model of nurse care managers, social workers, patient navigators, and disease-specific coordinators. The labor is expensive, finite, and concentrated in a few high-leverage settings: post-discharge from hospitalization, oncology, transplant, maternal-fetal medicine, complex pediatrics, and high-risk capitated populations. Outside those settings, most coordination work is done by patients and families, with only the most acute crises rising to professional attention.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The reason this has been resistant to digital tools is that the data infrastructure addressed the visible parts of coordination (records, appointments, referrals as data records) without addressing the harder parts (orchestrating activity across systems, watching for things that fall through, keeping the patient and family engaged). A patient portal that lets the patient see their records is genuinely useful and has improved access for many patients; it has not changed the rate at which referrals get lost, appointments slip past their optimal window, or post-discharge plans degrade.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed the workflow shape is the combination of two trends. First, the data infrastructure has matured to the point where the assistant can read across systems with reasonable reliability: the EHR, the referral system, the scheduling system, the records-release workflow, the pharmacy system, and (with HIE participation) records from outside institutions. Second, large language models can carry on the kind of relational, multi-step, context-aware conversations that the human coordinator carries on, while the deterministic-orchestration layer (workflow engine, tool-calling agent, milestone tracker) handles the deterministic parts of the coordination work.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "data infrastructure that the patient navigates manually" to "coordination assistant that navigates the data infrastructure on the patient's behalf and engages the patient conversationally for the parts that need the patient's input." The assistant's value is concentrated in three places: the orchestration layer that tracks milestones across providers and surfaces the right action at the right moment, the conversational layer that engages the patient in plain language without requiring them to learn the institutional workflow, and the escalation layer that catches the cases where coordination is degrading and routes them to a human coordinator before they fall through.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Care Coordination Assistant Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care coordination assistant is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (active care plans, active referrals, upcoming appointments, recent encounters, current medications, conversation history), access to a structured library of journey-specific protocols and institutional clinical content, and a careful set of tools for reading across systems (EHR, referral-management system, scheduling system, records-release workflow, pharmacy system, durable-medical-equipment workflow, home-health workflow, HIE), for proposing actions (schedule an appointment, request a records release, route a question to the care team, escalate to a human coordinator), and for maintaining the longitudinal coordination state (tracking each milestone of each active care plan toward closure).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is, like the chronic-disease coach, a stream of conversational episodes. The triggers, however, are different from the chronic-disease-coach triggers. The chronic-disease coach triggers on biometric data, on care-plan milestones, on patient-initiated questions, and on scheduled check-ins. The care coordination assistant triggers on those same signals but also on care-coordination-specific events: a discharge event from the hospital (start the post-discharge journey), a referral order from a clinician (start the referral-completion milestone tracking), a scheduled appointment (prepare the patient, confirm the records flow, follow up after), a missed appointment (re-engage the patient, surface the reason, propose a reschedule), an event in an external system (the cardiologist's office sent over their notes; the imaging center confirmed the appointment; the home-health agency completed the initial visit), or a coordination-degradation signal (a referral that has not closed within the expected window; a records-release request that has not been completed; a follow-up appointment that was scheduled past the recommended window).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The assistant's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Journey enrollment and care-plan ingestion.** When the patient enters a coordination journey (admitted to the hospital with a heart attack and approaching discharge; diagnosed with cancer and starting a multi-specialty workup; pregnant and entering prenatal care), the assistant ingests the relevant care plan, breaks it into trackable milestones, and engages the patient with an introduction to the journey. The care plan is signed by the patient's clinical team. The assistant operates within the care plan; deviation requires either care-plan revision or escalation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Milestone-based engagement.** Each care plan decomposes into milestones: a follow-up appointment to be scheduled within a window, a referral to be completed within a window, a records release to be processed, a medication to be picked up, a home-health visit to be completed, a piece of durable medical equipment to be delivered, a lab to be drawn at a specific time, a specialist consult to be obtained. The assistant tracks each milestone toward closure and engages the patient at the moments where engagement is needed: nudge to schedule, nudge to attend, nudge to follow up, nudge to call the clinic if something has not happened.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-provider context maintenance.** The assistant maintains a unified view of the patient across providers and settings, drawing from the institution's EHR, from external records via HIE participation, from referral-management data, from scheduling data, from pharmacy data, and from external-system reports. The unified view is the foundation of the assistant's coordination value: a patient asking "did the cardiologist get my records?" should not have to wait while the patient navigates the records-release workflow themselves; the assistant looks across the systems, surfaces the answer, and proposes the next action if there is one.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Information continuity across encounters.** When the patient sees a new clinician, the assistant ensures the right information accompanies the patient: the discharge summary, recent labs, recent imaging, the medication list, the relevant specialist notes. The institutional records-release workflow is the deterministic substrate; the assistant orchestrates it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-initiated coordination questions.** The patient asks "what was that appointment again?" or "where do I go for the imaging?" or "I think I missed something on the discharge instructions; can you remind me?" or "do I need a referral for that?" or "what does my deductible look like for the next visit?" Each is a coordination question; the assistant answers within scope using grounded retrieval, and escalates outside scope.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Scheduled and event-driven proactive engagement.** The day before a scheduled appointment, the assistant nudges the patient with the appointment details, confirms the records flow, and asks if the patient wants to flag anything for the visit. The day of, the assistant confirms attendance and addresses no-show risk. The day after, the assistant follows up to surface any issues from the visit and to capture any new milestones the visit produced.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Records-flow orchestration.** When the patient is moving from one provider to another, the assistant proactively orchestrates the records flow: requesting the source records from the previous provider, confirming receipt at the destination, and surfacing any gaps to the patient or to the human coordinator. The records flow is a deterministic-orchestration problem; the assistant handles the orchestration with the patient's consent and within the institutional records-release policy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Family-and-caregiver integration.** Where the patient has a designated family caregiver (a spouse, an adult child, a designated proxy), the assistant supports the caregiver's engagement with appropriate consent. Caregivers often do most of the coordination work for older patients and complex-pediatrics patients; the assistant's design accommodates the caregiver as a co-user.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social-determinants overlay.** Coordination is not only clinical: a patient who cannot afford transportation to the cardiac rehab will not attend; a patient whose work schedule conflicts with the program will not adhere; a patient with low health literacy will struggle with multi-step instructions. The assistant integrates social-determinants signals (where the institution has them) and routes social-determinants concerns to care-navigation pathways where the institution has them, with explicit recognition that the assistant is not a social worker.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Escalation to human coordinators.** When milestones are degrading, when patterns suggest worsening, when the patient discloses something concerning, when the conversation moves outside the assistant's scope, the assistant escalates to a human coordinator. The escalation is warm: full conversation context, the relevant milestone state, the proposed next action, with the assistant staying present until the human coordinator engages.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team reporting.** The patient's care team (the PCP, the specialists, the discharge nurse, the case manager) has visibility into the assistant's interactions through structured summaries: real-time alerts for milestone-degradation events, periodic coordination-status reports, and event-triggered summaries of patient-initiated questions that are clinically relevant.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Long-term-relationship maintenance, with care-coordination-specific calibration.** The assistant maintains conversation history, stated preferences, and prior journey history. Unlike the chronic-disease coach, the care coordination assistant is often deployed in episodic patterns (the post-discharge journey ends after 30 to 90 days; the maternity journey ends after the postpartum period). The assistant supports respectful off-boarding with structured handoff to the patient's longitudinal care team and to other longitudinal-engagement tools (the chronic-disease coach, the mental-health support tool) as appropriate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface, give it tool access to the EHR, and have it coordinate the patient's care. This breaks in several specific ways, each of which has clinical, operational, and engagement consequences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no consistent multi-system view.** Without a deterministic data layer that aggregates across the EHR, the referral system, the scheduling system, the records-release workflow, the pharmacy system, the HIE, and external-system reports, the LLM has fragmented context. The patient asking "did Dr. Patel's office get my records?" cannot be answered without checking the records-release workflow's status. The LLM hallucinating a "yes, your records were sent" answer when the records-release request has not actually been completed is a coordination failure with downstream cost.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of milestone state.** Care plans decompose into milestones with explicit completion semantics: scheduled, attended, no-showed, rescheduled, cancelled, completed, lost-to-follow-up. The state transitions follow specific rules. A milestone tracker is a deterministic component; the LLM is not equipped to maintain milestone state correctly across long horizons.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of windowing.** Care plans have implicit and explicit windows: "follow up with cardiology within two weeks." A scheduled appointment three weeks out is a coordination failure that should be escalated. The deterministic windowing logic is not LLM-territory; the LLM should be told the milestone is out-of-window and respond accordingly, not be expected to compute the window from prose.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of escalation triggers.** Coordination escalation is triggered by specific patterns: a missed appointment, a stalled referral, a records-release request that has not closed, a no-show pattern, a patient-disclosed coordination problem (transportation, financial, language barrier), a patient-disclosed clinical concern. The escalation logic is deterministic per institutional policy; the LLM proposes the action and the deterministic layer enforces it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of cross-institutional information-flow rules.** The records-release workflow has specific rules: the requesting clinician must be authorized, the patient must consent (or the consent must be on file), the format must match the receiving system's requirements, certain data classes (mental health, substance use, HIV) have additional protections under 42 CFR Part 2 and state-specific rules. The LLM should not be improvising on records-release; the deterministic workflow should be doing the work, and the LLM should be the conversational surface.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model hallucinates clinical content when grounding is weak.** A patient asking "what should I bring to the cardiology appointment?" should get an answer grounded in the institution's pre-visit instructions for cardiology, not a freestyled list. A patient asking "what does this medication do?" should get an answer grounded in the institution's patient-education content. The clinical-content RAG with strict citation grounding is the architectural floor.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to engage proactively.** The assistant's value is concentrated in proactive engagement: nudge before the appointment, follow up after the appointment, surface the next milestone at the right moment. The proactive engagement is scheduled by the engagement layer based on milestone state and care-plan windows; the LLM does not initiate proactive engagement on its own.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to stop pestering the patient.** Coordination is high-touch by nature: many milestones, many small touchpoints, many possible nudges. A coordination assistant that engages too aggressively gets opted out of, as with the chronic-disease coach. The institutional engagement policy specifies maximum frequency, quiet hours, opt-out granularity, and patient-controlled dial-back.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications specific to care coordination.** The conversation surfaces appointment information (location, time, reason), specialist information, medication information, and inferred clinical context (the patient is being followed for a recent cardiac event). The combination is sensitive PHI. Cross-institutional records flow has additional considerations under the Information Blocking Rule, state-specific patient-record-access laws, 42 CFR Part 2 for substance-use treatment data, and state-specific mental-health privacy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of patient consent for cross-institutional data flow.** The patient's consent for record sharing is not blanket. Some patients consent to broad sharing within an integrated delivery network. Some patients do not. Some states require explicit consent for HIE participation. The records-release workflow encodes consent state; the LLM should not be the consent-enforcement layer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of family-caregiver consent.** The patient may have authorized a family caregiver to act on their behalf or to receive coordination updates. The authorization is governed by HIPAA, state-specific health-information-access laws, and institutional policy. The consent-state for caregiver access is encoded in the consent-record; the LLM should not be making caregiver-access decisions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of coordination dignity.** A coordination assistant that talks down to patients ("did you remember to schedule your appointment?"), nags ("you really should follow up on this"), or surveils ("we noticed you haven't logged into the portal in three weeks") is a coordination assistant patients close. The relational tone, the listener-first conversation pattern, the respect-the-patient's-time discipline, and the warmth-without-condescension calibration are part of the architecture, not emergent properties.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when the journey ends.** A post-discharge journey ends. A maternity journey ends. A care-coordination-after-cancer-treatment journey transitions to survivorship. The off-boarding events, the structured handoff to the longitudinal care team, and the transition to other longitudinal-engagement tools (chronic-disease coach, mental-health support) are part of the architecture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Coordination Assistant Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.8 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening with continuous emergency screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, longitudinal-context loading, citation grounding, behavior-change-stage tracking, crisis-screening, companion-pattern avoidance. The care coordination assistant adds eight structural commitments those recipes did not have.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-system orchestration as architectural primitive.** The assistant reads across the EHR, the referral system, the scheduling system, the records-release workflow, the pharmacy system, the home-health workflow, the durable-medical-equipment workflow, and external systems via HIE. The unified view is the assistant's foundation; without it the assistant is a chatbot, not a coordinator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-plan-as-code with milestone decomposition.** Each journey is encoded as a structured care plan with milestones, windows, completion semantics, dependencies, and escalation criteria. The plans are owned by the institution's clinical leadership for the journey type (cardiac discharge, oncology, maternity, complex pediatrics, etc.), version-controlled, reviewed annually. The assistant operates within the plan; deviation requires care-plan revision or escalation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Milestone-tracking pipeline with explicit state machines.** Each milestone has an explicit state machine (proposed, scheduled, confirmed, attended, completed, no-show, rescheduled, cancelled, lost-to-follow-up). The state transitions are driven by events from the underlying systems (the EHR records the appointment was attended; the referral system marks the referral closed; the records-release workflow confirms records were transmitted) and by patient-disclosed events from the conversation. The pipeline is deterministic, not LLM-managed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Records-flow orchestration with consent enforcement.** The records-flow workflow is a first-class architectural primitive: requests for records, transmissions of records, confirmations of receipt, gap-detection. The workflow runs deterministically with consent-state checks at every step. The assistant is the conversational surface for the workflow, not the workflow itself.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-institutional integration with HIE and direct-connect partners.** The assistant operates in a multi-institutional reality. The patient's records may live across multiple EHRs at multiple institutions. The HIE may provide partial visibility. Direct-connect arrangements between institutions may provide better visibility for high-volume referral patterns. The integration architecture accommodates the heterogeneous data landscape.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Family-and-caregiver consent posture.** The assistant supports patient-designated caregivers as co-users where consent permits. The consent posture is encoded in the consent-record, refreshed periodically, and revocable. The institutional policy specifies what caregivers can and cannot do, and the assistant enforces the policy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social-determinants overlay with care-navigation handoff.** The assistant integrates social-determinants signals where the institution has them and routes social-determinants concerns to care-navigation pathways. The assistant is not a social worker; it surfaces the concern and routes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Escalation-to-human-coordinator infrastructure.** The assistant is deployed with backstop human-coordinator capacity. The escalation is warm: conversation context, milestone state, proposed action. The capacity is sized to the patient population and the expected escalation volume; under-sized capacity is a coordination gap.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle, conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Care-Coordination Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes care coordination specifically harder than the previous patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The patient is not the only user.** Family caregivers do most of the coordination work for older patients, complex-pediatrics patients, and patients with cognitive impairment. The assistant's design accommodates the caregiver as a legitimate user with appropriate consent. Many digital products in the category have failed because they were patient-only and the actual coordinator was the spouse, the adult child, or the proxy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The provider network is heterogeneous.** Patients receive care from providers inside the institution, providers in affiliated networks, providers in unaffiliated networks, providers across state lines, and providers in entirely different segments (mental health, dental, optometry, physical therapy). The assistant's information-flow architecture accommodates the heterogeneity, with explicit recognition that some providers are more reachable than others.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The information-flow infrastructure is uneven.** Within the institution, the EHR is the source of truth. Across institutions, the HIE provides partial visibility. Outside the HIE network, records flow by fax, by mail, and by patient hand-carry. The assistant's value is highest where the information-flow infrastructure is best; the assistant's value drops in regions and patient populations where the infrastructure is poor.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Coordination dignity is the engagement currency.** Patients have, often, been told a thousand times what they should do. The hundredth nudge from a coordination assistant is more likely to alienate than to motivate. The relational tone, the listener-first conversation pattern, the respect-the-patient's-time discipline, and the warmth-without-condescension calibration are most of the engagement engineering. Coordination assistants that get this wrong are coordination assistants patients close.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cultural and linguistic considerations are amplified.** Coordination requires cross-system navigation and multi-party communication; patients with limited English proficiency, with low health literacy, and with cultural framings that differ from the institution's framing experience disproportionate coordination friction. The assistant's per-language, per-cultural-context, per-reading-level calibration is essential.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social-determinants context is part of the coordination reality.** Transportation, work schedule, family caregiving, financial constraints, insurance benefits, language access. The assistant integrates these where the institution has the signals and routes to care-navigation where the institution has the pathways. The institution that has none of this and deploys a coordination assistant in isolation has built half the architecture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Mental-health comorbidity affects coordination.** Patients with active depression have lower follow-through rates. Patients with anxiety often delay or avoid coordination tasks. Patients with substance-use disorder may have specific coordination needs around 42 CFR Part 2 records. The assistant's mental-health-comorbidity awareness is part of its design, with explicit handoff to mental-health support tools (recipe 11.8) where indicated.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Caregiver burnout is real.** Family caregivers carrying a substantial coordination load are at elevated risk of burnout, depression, and their own health decline. The assistant's caregiver-engagement design includes explicit acknowledgment of caregiver context, surfacing of caregiver-support resources, and routing to caregiver-specific care-management programs where the institution has them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episodic-versus-longitudinal balance is delicate.** Some journeys are episodic (post-discharge for 30-90 days; post-procedure for 30 days; maternity for the prenatal-through-postpartum window). Some patients have multiple overlapping journeys (a heart failure patient discharged with a new cancer diagnosis is in two journeys at once). The architectural decision about whether a patient has one assistant relationship across all journeys or separate relationships per journey is a clinical-leadership decision that has implications for the conversation experience, the data model, and the engagement scheduling.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome demonstration is meaningful but is not always direct.** The coordination assistant's effect on readmission rate, on missed-appointment rate, on referral-completion rate, on records-flow completion rate, on patient-and-caregiver satisfaction, and on total cost of care for the population is the right outcome surface. The effect on individual patient clinical outcomes (an A1c reduction, a blood-pressure improvement) is mediated by the chronic-disease pathways the coordination supports; attribution is harder than for the chronic-disease coach.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Liability and regulatory positioning are nuanced.** Patient-facing care-coordination software does not typically reach the FDA SaMD bar (it does not provide diagnosis, does not interpret images, does not adjust medications), but it sits adjacent to that line. The Information Blocking Rule under the 21st Century Cures Act creates specific obligations around patient access to health information. State-specific patient-record-access laws apply. 42 CFR Part 2 applies for substance-use treatment data. State-specific mental-health-privacy statutes apply for mental-health records. The institutional regulatory and legal teams are involved from architectural design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The Cures Act and the Information Blocking Rule have changed the patient-record-access posture.** Patient access to electronic health information is broadly required, with specific obligations on healthcare providers, health IT developers, and HIEs to refrain from practices that interfere with the access, exchange, or use of EHI. <!-- TODO: verify; the Information Blocking Rule under the 21st Century Cures Act took effect in 2021 with specific compliance dates and ongoing rulemaking; specific compliance obligations vary by entity type and continue to evolve --> The implication for coordination assistants is that the assistant's information surface is broader than it would have been before 2021, with patients (and authorized caregivers) generally entitled to see most of their electronic health information, including notes, with specific narrow exceptions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The TEFCA framework provides national-scale interoperability infrastructure.** The Trusted Exchange Framework and Common Agreement, with the Recognized Coordinating Entity finalized and Qualified Health Information Networks operational, provides a national-scale interoperability infrastructure that augments existing regional HIEs. <!-- TODO: verify; TEFCA implementation has continued to evolve since the framework was finalized; specific QHIN participation, governance, and operational details vary --> Coordination assistants benefit from the broader information-flow infrastructure where it is operational.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR is the dominant API standard.** Most modern EHRs, patient-facing applications, and HIE participants support FHIR APIs for patient and clinical data access, including read access for the patient via the SMART-on-FHIR pattern with appropriate OAuth scoping. <!-- TODO: verify; FHIR support across major EHRs and patient-portal vendors is broad with version differences (R4 is most widely supported as of recent specifications); specific implementations vary --> The assistant's data layer is FHIR-native where possible, with custom integrations for non-FHIR systems.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The 21st Century Cures Act and CMS rulemaking have increased portability and transparency expectations.** Specific provisions including USCDI (United States Core Data for Interoperability), FHIR-API requirements for ONC-certified EHR technology, payer-side interoperability requirements (CMS-9115, CMS-0057), and Patient Access API requirements have collectively raised the floor for what coordination assistants can expect from the data infrastructure. <!-- TODO: verify; the CMS interoperability rulemaking continues to evolve with specific provisions and effective dates varying -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle multi-system orchestration well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from previous chapter 11 recipes maps to care coordination. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve patient context, retrieve referral state, retrieve appointment state, retrieve records-flow state, propose actions (schedule, request records, escalate), and post events for downstream operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid AI-plus-human-coordinator deployment is the dominant production pattern.** Most major deployments run a hybrid model: AI assistant for routine coordination, human coordinators for high-acuity cases, escalation cases, and patient-requested human contact. The economics work because the AI assistant handles the routine while the human coordinators focus where their judgment is most needed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome demonstration is solid for some specific journey types.** Post-discharge coordination programs have demonstrated meaningful reductions in 30-day readmission rates, particularly for cardiac, pulmonary, and surgical populations. <!-- TODO: verify; post-discharge coordination program outcome studies including the Care Transitions Intervention work and CMS Hospital Readmissions Reduction Program data document specific reductions in readmission rates with substantial heterogeneity by program design and population --> Maternity coordination programs have demonstrated improvements in prenatal visit adherence and postpartum follow-up rates. Oncology coordination programs have demonstrated improvements in time-to-treatment and patient-reported outcomes. The evidence base for AI-augmented coordination specifically is younger but is consistent with the broader coordination evidence.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity considerations are particularly relevant for coordination.** Care coordination disparities are well-documented across racial, ethnic, linguistic, socioeconomic, and geographic dimensions. <!-- TODO: verify; care-coordination disparities are documented in studies of post-discharge outcomes, referral completion, specialist access, and patient-experience measures across demographic groups --> An assistant that disproportionately serves patients with high digital fluency and broad provider-network access risks widening rather than narrowing the disparity. Per-cohort monitoring with explicit equity focus is essential.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for some segments.** Several mature commercial vendors offer coordination products at major-payer and major-health-system scale, with EHR integration, referral-management integration, scheduling integration, and (for some) FDA-cleared remote-monitoring components. Most major institutions deploying in this space run a hybrid: build a thin coordination-orchestration layer in-house, partner with vendors for journey-specific content and (sometimes) for the human-coordinator workforce, and integrate with the institution's care-management, telehealth, and clinical-record infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
